<ab><lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἄτταλος">Ἄτταλο<seg type="autopsy">ς</seg></name>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μένανδρος"><seg type="autopsy">Μ</seg>εν<lb n="2" break="no"/>άνδρ<seg type="autopsy"><unclear reason="damage">ο</unclear>υ</seg></name>  <w lemma="ὁ"><seg type="autopsy">το</seg>ῦ</w>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἄτταλος">Ἀτ<lb n="3" break="no"/><seg type="autopsy"><unclear reason="damage">τά</unclear></seg>λ<seg type="autopsy"><unclear reason="damage">ο</unclear></seg>υ</name></persName></persName></persName>  <w lemma="καί">κ<seg type="autopsy">αὶ</seg></w>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἀτταλίς">Ἀ<seg type="autopsy">τ</seg>τα<lb n="4" break="no"/><seg type="autopsy">λὶς</seg></name>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μενεκράτης"><seg type="autopsy">Μ<unclear reason="damage">ε</unclear></seg>ν<seg type="autopsy">εκρ</seg>ά<supplied reason="lost">τους</supplied></name></persName><lb n="5"/><name nymRef="#Ἄπφιος"><seg type="autopsy">Ἄπφιο</seg>ν</name></persName> <w lemma="ὁ">οἱ</w> <w lemma="ἱερεύς"><supplied reason="lost">ἱερ</supplied>εῖς</w>  <lb n="6"/><w lemma="ὁ"><seg type="autopsy">τῆς</seg></w>  <persName type="divine"><name nymRef="#Ἀφροδίτη"><seg type="autopsy">Ἀ</seg>φρο<seg type="autopsy">δείτης</seg></name></persName>  <lb n="7"/><w lemma="θεά"><seg type="autopsy"><unclear reason="damage">θ</unclear>εᾷ</seg></w>  <persName type="divine"><name nymRef="#Ἀφροδίτη"><seg type="autopsy">Ἀφ</seg>ροδεί<seg type="autopsy">τῃ</seg></name></persName>  <space unit="character" extent="1" dim="horizontal"/><lb n="8"/><supplied reason="lost"><w lemma="καί">καὶ</w>  <w lemma="ὁ">τῷ</w>  <w lemma="δῆμος">Δήμωι</w></supplied>  <space unit="character" extent="5" dim="horizontal"/></ab>
</div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p> Letters read by us are highlighted.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Attalos son of Menandros the son of Attalos, and Attalis Apphion daughter of Menekrates, priests of Aphrodite, for the goddess Aphrodite and the People</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of the group of column dedications from the Temple of Aphrodite: <ref type="inscription" n="1121" target="010004.xml"/> (=MAMA 437), <ref type="inscription" n="1122" target="010005.xml"/> (=MAMA 438), <ref type="inscription" n="1123" target="010006.xml"/> (=Reinach 122), <ref type="inscription" n="1124" target="010007.xml"/> (=MAMA 450), <ref type="inscription" n="1125" target="010008.xml"/> (=KRC 37+); see discussed by <bibl n="jmr1990">
                  <author>Reynolds</author>, 'Inscriptions and the Building of the Temple', <title>Aphrodisias Papers </title>(Ann Arbor, 1990), 37-40, 38</bibl>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p>b published from K&amp;R by <bibl n="cormack1964">Cormack, ABSA 59, 1964, 27, no. <citedRange>37</citedRange>
               </bibl>, whence <bibl n="PHI">
                  <author>McCabe</author>
                  <title level="m">PHI Aphrodisias</title>
                  <citedRange n="257035">156</citedRange>
               </bibl>; a and c unpublished</p>
         </div>
